HEADWORD: Amissibility
<hw>A*mis`si*bil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>amissibilit⟦eacute⟧</ets>. See <er>Amit</er>.]</ety> <def>The
quality of being amissible; possibility of being lost.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Notions of popular rights and the <qex>amissibility</qex> of
sovereign power for misconduct were alternately broached by the two
great religious parties of Europe.</q> <rj><qau>Hallam.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Amissible</ent>⟦br⟧
